		</div>
	
	</div>
    
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="108895978633494552"></a>
    
    <h2><font color="#000080"><!-- 2004-08-31 -->
    <a href="http://usefulinc.com/articles/2004/desktop-metadata"
                    title="external link">
    Metadata for the desktop
    </a>
    </font></h2>
    
    
    <p>
	<div style="clear:both;"></div><a href="http://usefulinc.com/articles/2004/desktop-metadata">2004: Metadata for the desktop</a>.&nbsp; This Edd Dumbill article provides worked examples and demonstration of the value of metadata (via RDF) on the desktop.&nbsp; It is rather interesting that it is automatically presumed that RDF expresses semantics, with little demonstration of how that occurs, except for some hand-waving around the use of &lt;dc:creator&gt;.<br /><br /><em>From 2004-07-04:</em> This was in the backlog of drafts.  There are more-recent topics concerning where the semantics are to be found in Dublin Core and other entity tag sets in XML and especially RDF.  This is going to be part of the development around <a href="http://orcmid.com/blog/2006/02/what-computers-know.asp">What Computers Know</a> as the progression is expanded.<div style="clear:both; padding-bottom: 0.25em;"></div>
    </p>
	<span class="byline">posted by orcmid
       at <a href="http://miser-theory.info/astraendo/pn/2006/02/metadata-for-desktop.asp">2/08/2006 03:15:00 PM</a></span>
	       
